The problem an index solves

Picture your weather_weatherreading table after a week of fetching. It's got thousands of rows — London, Tokyo, New York, all mixed together:

┌─────┬──────────┬─────────────┬───────────────────────┐
│ id  │   city   │ temperature │      recorded_at      │
├─────┼──────────┼─────────────┼───────────────────────┤
│ 1   │ London   │ 13.4        │ Jun 28 09:00          │
├─────┼──────────┼─────────────┼───────────────────────┤
│ 2   │ Tokyo    │ 27.8        │ Jun 28 09:00          │
├─────┼──────────┼─────────────┼───────────────────────┤
│ 3   │ New York │ 19.1        │ Jun 28 09:00          │
├─────┼──────────┼─────────────┼───────────────────────┤
│ 4   │ London   │ 14.1        │ Jun 28 10:00          │
├─────┼──────────┼─────────────┼───────────────────────┤
│ ... │ ...      │ ...         │ ... (5,000 more rows) │
└─────┴──────────┴─────────────┴───────────────────────┘

Now your chart asks the DB:

▎ "Give me all London readings, sorted by time."

Without an index: the database has no shortcut. It reads every single row, top to bottom, checking "is this London? is this London?" — 5,000 checks to find maybe 168 London rows. Slow, and it gets slower as data grows.

With an index on (city, recorded_at): the database keeps a pre-sorted lookup on the side, like the index at the back of a textbook:

London    → rows 1, 4, 9, 12, ...   (already in time order)
New York  → rows 3, 7, 11, ...
Tokyo     → rows 2, 5, 8, ...

So when you ask for London, it jumps straight to the London section — no scanning the whole table. Instant.

Why those two columns specifically

The index has to match how you actually query. Our every query is "filter by city, then sort by recorded_at." So we index that exact pair. Indexing a random column like temperature would be useless here — we never search "find all rows where temp = 14.1."

📌 Rule of thumb: you index the columns you filter and sort on.

---
That's the whole idea — a side lookup so the DB skips the full scan. The ordering = ['-recorded_at'] part is unrelated and simple: it just sets the default newest-first sort so you don't retype .order_by('-recorded_at') every query.

