❯ so u mean we are doing indexing and indexing mean like bookmarking is it?

Yes — exactly that, you've got it. 🎯 "Bookmarking" is a really good way to hold it. Let me just sharpen it by one notch so it's rock-solid:

A bookmark = one ribbon marking one page you jump to.

An index = a whole sorted directory that says where everything is.

Think of the back of a textbook:

INDEX
─────────────
London ...... pages 1, 4, 9, 12
New York .... pages 3, 7, 11
Tokyo ....... pages 2, 5, 8

You don't read the book cover to cover hunting for "London" — you flip to the index, it points you straight there. The database does the same thing: we tell it "keep a sorted directory on (city, recorded_at)," and from then on every "find London, by time" query jumps straight to the answer instead of scanning all 5,000 rows.

So your instinct is right — it's bookmarking for the database, done automatically and kept sorted.

One tiny but important add: an index isn't free. The DB has to update the directory every time you insert a new row (just like a textbook index would need reprinting if you added pages). That's why you don't index every column — only the ones you actually search/sort by. For us that's (city, recorded_at). 👍
